ONA Demo: Window-to-Window Transitions

Saqr Lab

2026-02-09

What is ONA?

Ordered Network Analysis (ONA) computes window-to-window transitions where:

  • Every active state in window t connects to every active state in window t+1
  • Multiple codes can be active simultaneously (unlike TNA single-state sequences)
  • Preserves temporal order while allowing co-occurrence

Example 1: Simple Sequential

When only one code is active per timepoint, ONA behaves like TNA:

# Simple sequence: A -> B -> C -> D
simple <- data.frame(
  A = c(1, 0, 0, 0),
  B = c(0, 1, 0, 0),
  C = c(0, 0, 1, 0),
  D = c(0, 0, 0, 1)
)
simple
##   A B C D
## 1 1 0 0 0
## 2 0 1 0 0
## 3 0 0 1 0
## 4 0 0 0 1
model_simple <- ona(simple, type = "frequency")
model_simple$weights
##   A B C D
## A 0 1 0 0
## B 0 0 1 0
## C 0 0 0 1
## D 0 0 0 0
splot(model_simple,
      title = "Simple Sequence: A -> B -> C -> D",
      layout = "circle",
      edge_labels = TRUE,
      node_size = 0.1,
      edge_color = "#003355")

Example 2: Multiple Active Codes (ONA-Specific)

This is where ONA differs from TNA - multiple codes can be active simultaneously:

# t1: A and B active, t2: C and D active
multi <- data.frame(
  A = c(1, 0),
  B = c(1, 0),
  C = c(0, 1),
  D = c(0, 1)
)
cat("Timepoint 1: A and B active\nTimepoint 2: C and D active\n")
## Timepoint 1: A and B active
## Timepoint 2: C and D active
multi
##   A B C D
## 1 1 1 0 0
## 2 0 0 1 1
model_multi <- ona(multi, type = "frequency")
model_multi$weights
##   A B C D
## A 0 0 1 1
## B 0 0 1 1
## C 0 0 0 0
## D 0 0 0 0

All four transitions are captured: A->C, A->D, B->C, B->D

splot(model_multi,
      title = "Multi-Code Transitions",
      layout = "circle",
      edge_labels = TRUE,
      node_size = 0.1,
      curvature = 0.3,
      edge_color = "#003355")

Simulated one-hot encoded data representing student learning behaviors during an online course session. Each row is a 30-second window.

set.seed(42)

Activity Pattern

library(ggplot2)

saqr_long <- tidyr::pivot_longer(
  saqr_data,
  cols = -window,
  names_to = "Strategy",
  values_to = "Active"
)

ggplot(saqr_long, aes(x = window, y = Strategy, fill = factor(Active))) +
  geom_tile(color = "white", linewidth = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("0" = "#f0f0f0", "1" = "#003355"),
                    labels = c("Inactive", "Active")) +
  labs(title = "Learning Strategy Activation Over Time",
       x = "Window (30-sec intervals)", y = "Strategy", fill = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

ONA Analysis

model_saqr <- ona(
  saqr_data,
  type = "relative",
  cols = c("Planning", "Content", "Discussion", "Practice", "Reflection")
)

cat("Transition probabilities:\n")

round(model_saqr$weights, 3)

Network Visualization

Example 4: Multiple Students

Transitions are computed within each student and then aggregated:

multi_student <- data.frame(
  student = c(rep("Alice", 4), rep("Bob", 4)),
  A = c(1,0,0,0, 0,0,1,0),
  B = c(0,1,0,0, 1,0,0,0),
  C = c(0,0,1,0, 0,1,0,0),
  D = c(0,0,0,1, 0,0,0,1)
)

cat("Alice: A -> B -> C -> D\nBob: B -> C -> A -> D\n")
## Alice: A -> B -> C -> D
## Bob: B -> C -> A -> D
multi_student
##   student A B C D
## 1   Alice 1 0 0 0
## 2   Alice 0 1 0 0
## 3   Alice 0 0 1 0
## 4   Alice 0 0 0 1
## 5     Bob 0 1 0 0
## 6     Bob 0 0 1 0
## 7     Bob 1 0 0 0
## 8     Bob 0 0 0 1
model_students <- ona(
  multi_student,
  type = "frequency",
  cols = c("A", "B", "C", "D"),
  params = list(actor_col = "student")
)

cat("Aggregated transitions:\n")
## Aggregated transitions:
model_students$weights
##   A B C D
## A 0 1 0 1
## B 0 0 2 0
## C 1 0 0 1
## D 0 0 0 0
splot(model_students,
      title = "Multi-Student Aggregated Network",
      layout = "circle",
      edge_labels = TRUE,
      node_size = 0.1,
      curvature = 0.2,
      edge_color = "#003355")

Summary

The key difference between TNA and ONA:

  • TNA: One state per timepoint, sequential transitions
  • ONA: Multiple states per timepoint, all-to-all window transitions

The ona() function returns a TNA-compatible object that works with splot().
